Sure! Let's go step by step. I’ll guide you through writing a simple Python program and running it in OpenShift using the command line.

Step 1: Write a simple Python program

Create a file called app.py with this content:

# app.py
print("Hello, OpenShift!")

Step 2: Create a Dockerfile (optional if using S2I Python image)

If you want to use a Dockerfile:

# Dockerfile
FROM python:3.11-slim
WORKDIR /app
COPY app.py /app
CMD ["python", "app.py"]


If you prefer, OpenShift has Python S2I images (source-to-image) that let you skip writing a Dockerfile.

Step 3: Log in to OpenShift
oc login https://<openshift-api-server> --token=<your-token>

Step 4: Create a new project (namespace)
oc new-project my-python-app

Step 5: Deploy using oc new-app

Option 1: Using local source code with S2I Python image

oc new-app python:3.11~. --name=my-python-app


Explanation:

python:3.11 → OpenShift’s S2I Python image

~. → Use current directory as source

Option 2: Using Dockerfile

oc new-app . --name=my-python-app

Step 6: Check the build
oc get builds


Follow the build logs:

oc logs -f bc/my-python-app

Step 7: Run the application

Once built, OpenShift will create a Pod. You can check it:

oc get pods


Run the app in the Pod:

oc logs -f pod/<pod-name>


You should see:

Hello, OpenShift!


✅ Summary:

Write app.py

Use either Dockerfile or S2I Python image

Log in and create project

oc new-app to deploy

Check build and logs
